e.talents.XIcDsaW4D8wScezw]{Accurate Shot}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Explosives)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GHmXS9zGNx3PWYZc]{Master Tradesman (Gunsmith)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.769B469sqx6FXPfn]{Rapid Reload}<br /><strong>Trappings</strong>: Leadbelcher Cannon, Shrapnel Scars, 3 Cannon Balls</p>\n<h3><strong>IV. @Compendium[ogre-kingdom-wfrp4e.careers-ok.0M8eH7jRJSbiS7bB]{Thunderfist}</strong></h3>\n<p><strong>Status</strong>: Gold 1<br /><strong>Skills</strong>: @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.iYan4z52v7HYM9u9]{Drive}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate}<br /><strong>Talents</strong>: @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GHmXS9zGNx3PWYZc]{Master Tradesman (Explosives)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.cygaI9gq4BQJvbB5]{Sniper}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RWJrupj9seau0w31]{Strike to Injure}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.phXzaUxl3mFqkmDq]{Sure Shot}<br /><strong>Trappings</strong>: Unit of Leadbelchers</p>","_id":"VzcSz0fRZNkSh5uO"}
{"_id":"j7Phge70bHwkmpyd","name":"Ogre Religion","permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.eeAxjFF7fr9IIesD"}},"content":"<p><strong>Seat of Power:</strong> None</p>\n<p><strong>Head of the Cult: </strong>Skrag the Slaughterer</p>\n<p><strong>Primary Orders:</strong> None</p>\n<p><strong>Major Festivals:</strong> The Great Feast</p>\n<p><strong>Popular Holy Books:</strong> None</p>\n<p><strong>Common Holy Symbols: </strong>Ring of Jagged Teeth</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Great Maw, the great devouring god, is the manifestation of the Ogre&rsquo;s endless hunger. Known for its massive size stretching miles wide, it is a being made manifest after the forces of Cathay summoned a comet of pure Warpstone many thousands of years ago to wipe out their Ogre neighbors. They failed, despite wiping out most of the Ogre population, and instead help create a creature twisted and reformed by the Ogre&rsquo;s fears and natural lust for power. Thus, the titanic Great Maw we know today was born, with endless rows of teeth, a body stretching from one end of the world to the other and an all-consuming hunger to match. It&rsquo;s depicted as an enormous row of jagged teeth forming a circle representing the Maw&rsquo;s endless rows of teeth stretching deep into the darkness. The Great Maw is located south-east of the Ancient Giant Lands, past the Mountains of Mourn.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Worshippers</strong></h3>\n<p>The Great Maw is worshipped by all Ogres throughout the Old World and beyond and is the primary dominating religion across the entirety of the Ogre Kingdoms. Even Ogres thousands of miles away from the Mountains of Mourn, who know little of The Great Maw, are at the mercy of its constant hunger, consuming in its name. Ogres adopting different religions and cultures will use foreign gods as surrogates to The Great Maw, unknowingly or not. Even Ogre worshippers of the Dark Gods are not immune to its influence. The main goal of every Ogre is to grow as fat and powerful as possible.</p>\n<p>The cult has no orders, but instead sadistic priests known as Butchers, mostly nomadic, who are tasked with being the head cooks and spellcasters of many Ogre tribes. Butchers never wear gut-plates as a sign of confidence to their connection with the Maw, trading them in for messy aprons, caked in blood and filth, to hold their terrifying looking cooking utensils for ritualistically prepared dinners.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Holy Sites</strong></h3>\n<p>Maw temples and shrines are found in all Ogre tribes, outposts, and in many caves within the Mountains of Mourn. There is no definitive great temple to the Maw but instead thousands of sites dedicated to it. These sites are constructed by digging up massive holes in the soil and setting up painted rocks and charms depicting the symbols of the Maw. These pits are then filled as much as possible with the flesh and bones of various animals, monsters and species as tribute. The Maw-that-Walks, Skrag the Slaughterer is the closest thing to a reigning authority amongst the Butchers and Slaughtermasters of the Maw within the Mountains of Mourn. Skrag&rsquo;s name strikes awe and fear into any Ogre that utters his name, his devotion to the Maw so great he leaves even the hardiest Ogre Tyrants quaking at his presence.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Penances</strong></h3>\n<p>The Great Maw has no penances. All it demands of its followers is to consume as many creatures and to grow as fat as possible to satiate its never-ending hunger.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Strictures</strong></h3>\n<p>&bull; Eat, consume and grow fat.</p>\n<p>&bull; Eat as messily as possible.</p>\n<p>&bull; Never leave a meal unfinished.</p>\n<p>&bull; If challenged by another, the victorious Ogre must eat their opponent.</p>"}
{"_id":"jIEc62Vs34NCfDXG","name":"Irongut","permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.EtmVIm4dN41VqVkp"}},"content":"<p>&ldquo;Ironguts are the Ogres of any given tribe that have the most status and the best armour and weapons, acting as the rock-hard fighting elite of their tribe's Tyrant. They go into battle armed with massive two-handed weapons, be they enormous scimitars, rocks bolted to tree boughs with iron bands, or simply gigantic versions of the traditional Ogre club. Ironguts wear large, ornamental gut-plates to show off their elite standing and cover their meaty arms and boulder-like heads in heavy armour plating cobbled together from various conquests over the years.</p>\n<p>Although not markedly superior in strength to their fellows, Ironguts are afforded great respect, as they are usually hand-picked by the Tyrant himself. For this reason, a unit of Ironguts may well include the Tyrant's immediate family, where another might be comprised of his favorite drinking cronies. That said, it's not unheard of for the bulk of some especially formidable Ogre tribes to be made up of Ironguts. This is especially true amongst rich or powerful Ogre tribes, who can afford the expensive equipment and weaponry needed to equip a unit of Ironguts.</p>\n<p>Very little can stand before a full-blooded Ironguts charge. Any enemy troops that aren't hurled to the ground by the impact of the collision are subsequently smashed, pulped or hacked apart by the massive weapons the Ironguts carry. Any who survive that barrage of brutality risk being stomped into the dirt under by the Ironguts metal-shod feet.</p>\n<p>Ironguts are often used to spearhead an important attack or are held in reserve by some Tyrants and used to bolster the battle line. A common Ogre saying when things are going badly is that it's &lsquo;down to the Ironguts&rsquo;. Regardless of when or where they are deployed or how badly they are outnumbered, there is always a chance such a rock-hard formation can batter their way to victory.</p>\n<p>Ironguts are also typified by an unshakable belief in their own power and superiority. This stems from the extensive eating contest that Ironguts go through to prove their worth and themselves both in a crude type of initiation ritual and occasionally just to show off. The Ironguts will dispatch their intestinal prowess by eating a range of unpalatable items ranging from rusty nails, hard gravel, iron-banded cartwheels and even chains and armor, which is particularly hard to chew. It was one of these contests which gave the rise to the myth of &lsquo;When Bolgut Fell Ill&rsquo;, a favorite amongst Ogre whelps due to its fanciful nature. After all, everyone knows there is little an Irongut cannot digest.</p>\n<p>Ironguts go into battle as a powerful shock force. At the Battle of Magma River, the Rocksplitter tribe was ambushed by a huge Skaven horde. Hemmed in on all sides and outnumbered hundreds to one, the Ogre army was being slowly driven back towards the river of red-hot lava from which the battle took its name. Just when all seemed lost, a furious charge by the army's Ironguts broke a hole in the Skaven line. Swinging to left and right, the Ironguts enlarged the breach while splattering gore in sweeping arcs. Realizing their center was gone beneath the battering swipes of the Ironguts, the entire Skaven army lost heart, turned tail and bolted for it, securing both a great Ogre victory and the ensuing feast of magma-roasted ratmen.&rdquo;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>&mdash;Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Species:&nbsp;</strong>Ogre</p>\n<p><strong>Class:&nbsp;</strong>Warrior</p>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">Irongut Advance Scheme</h3>\n<table style=\"width: 640px; height: 34px;\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\n<td style=\"height: 17px; width: 60px; text-align: center;\">WS</td>\n<td style=\"height: 17px;